RONALD CLARK LIVED IN A LIBRARY AS A KID GROWING UP.
IT WAS COMMON FOR LIBRARIANS TO LIVE IN LIBRARIES IN THE 1950'S AND 1960'S.
HIS DAD GOT A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN OF THE LIBRARY.
HE THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS RICH BUT HIS FATHER TOLD THEM THEY WERE POOR.
HE DIDN'T FEEL NORMAL LIVING IN A LIBRARY AND FELT WEIRD BRINGING HIS FRIENDS THERE.
HIS DAD'S LIBRARY LOOKED VERY WAXED AND WAS ALWAYS CLEAN.
IT ALLOWED HIM TO READ A LOT AND HAVE A LOT OF BOOKS READILY AVAILABLE TO HIM AS GROWING UP.
IT HELPED HIM GET A JOB AS PROFESSOR.
HE SHOWED HIS FATHER THE DOOR WITH HIS NAME ON WHEN HE BECAME A PROFESSOR
HIS DAD DIDN'T SAY MUCH BUT THATS HOW HE WAS
HIS DAD WANTED MORE FOR HIM THAN HIS DAD HAD.
ROBERT CLARK GREW UP IN A LIBRARY IN THE 1950'S
HE THOUGHT HE WAS RICH BUT HIS FATHER TOLD HIM HE WAS POOR.
HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN OF THE LIBRARY
HE WOULD WAX THE FLOORS AND BOOKSHELVES AND KEEP IT VERY CLEAN
ROBERT ENJOYED READING THE BOOKS AND IT WAS A BIG HOBBY FOR HIM
HE SHOWED HIS FATHER HIS NAME ON HIS DOOR AT HIS OFFICE
HIS FATHER DIDN'T SAY MUCH BUT THAT'S THE WAY HE WAS
HIS FATHER WANTED HIM TO HAVE MORE OPPORTUNITIES THAN HE DID.
